column168: I, John Vergis Environmental Officer for the Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway, was called out to our yard in Brewster, OH on 7-4-2016 at 1530 hrs. for a possible leaking car GATX 211434.  The car inspector reported a strong odor coming from this car.  When I arrived and investigated with my gas meter, I found that vapor was coming our from around the manway lid.  I cut the seal and opened the lid and found that the manway gasket was missing. I installed a new gasket and resealed the car and released it for shipment.

BRITTANY RESPONDED TO A REPORTED LEAKING PACKAGE AT PD-11 BAY 148. SHE USED THE DECISION TREE, RESPONSE SHEETS, AND PROPER P.P.E., FOR CORROSIVE LIQUIDS. THE LIQUID DID NOT ESCAPE THE BOX. SHE TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE TO THE PROCESSING AREA. I NEUTRALIZED AND ABSORBED ALL LIQUID. ALL WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE DMP. THERE WAS NO SALVAGEABLE PORTION.

I, BILL HIGGINS, FOUND THE PACKAGE IN PACKAGE CAR NO. 146158 IN THE WEST SHORT METRO AREA. I FIRST CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE WHICH LED ME TO USE THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVES. I DONNED GOGGLES, BOOTS, APRON, AND SILVER SHIELDS UNDER HEAVY GLOVES. I USED PH TAPE AND FOUND SPILLED MATERIAL TO BE OUTSIDE THE 6-9 RANGE. I APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND MIXED WITH A STIR STICK UNTIL THE MATERIAL WAS TESTING WITHIN THE 6-9 RANGE. I THEN USED A BROOM AND PLASTIC DUSTPAN TO PLACE ALL THE SPILL INTO A LINED SPILL TUB AFTER I HAD ABSORBED THE ENTIRE SPILL WITH UNIVERSAL ABSORBANT. I THEN PLACED THE DAMAGED PACKAGE INTO THE SPILL TUB. THERE WERE NO CONTAMINATED PACKAGES. I THEN TRANSPORTED THE SPILL TO THE D.M.P. AREA TO BE PROCESSED ACCORDING TO THE WASTE DISPOSAL CHART FOR A FULL DMP FACILITY.

column168: Eco Energy tractor and trailer were stopped at a stop sign E/B Bringle Ferry Rd the other part was S/B Hwy 8 at a high rate of speed. The Eco Energy driver observed the other party approaching and remained stopped at the stop sign. The other party attempted to turn right onto Bringle Ferry Rd. Due to the high rate of speed the drive was not able to negotiate the turn and he crossed over the center line and collided with the trailer at the approximate mid point. The collision caused the vehicle to go almost completely out from under the trailer. The loading/unloading plumbing was destroyed and the underside of the tank received major damage. The content of the tank had been delivered at the prior stop and there was no loss of product.

column168: At the R&L Carriers terminal in Wilmington, OH, a 55 gallon poly drum of UN1791 Biosperse arrived bulging and leaking from the top bung cap.  It appeared as if the drum had been over pressurized causing the leak to occur.  The bung cap released approximately 4 ounces of material to the top of the drum body. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted. An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release and depressurize the drum.  The drum was relieved of the excess pressure, cleaned and over packed as a precaution.  The over packed drum was left on site for R&L personnel to manage. Any waste generated was taken offsite for proper disposal.

The damaged pail released approximately 1 pint of material to the dock floor.  NO soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release and over pack the pail. The contractor cleaned the release with granular absorbents and over packed the damaged pail.  The waste was taken offsite and properly disposed of and the over-packed pail was left on site for R&L personnel to manage.

column168: On July 2, 2016 at 09:15 hours personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered SHQX 5371, a residue tank car of Propane, leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Omnitrax Logistics, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2016-07-02-00083).  Summit Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene. Prior to Summits arrival, a local CSX manager inspected the car and found the vapor line valve was not fully closed- at this time he closed the valve and stopped the release.  Upon Summits arrival they discovered that the secondary securement plug on the vapor line was not installed; Summit also discovered the secondary securement plug on the sample line was not installed.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Dax Eymard 956-592-4216).  Summit ensured all other closure valves were closed and secondary securement plugs installed wrench tight.  The car was released for transportation.  No Special switching move was required.    NARRI: 5(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90  Cause Code: 134

column168: THE TRADEBE TANKER ARRIVED ON SITE AND CHECKED IN AT APPROXIMATELY 5 AM ON JUNE 13 201. THE BULK TANKER WAS LOADED AND AFTER THE LOAD WAS CHECKED AND THE PAPERWORK SIGNED, THE DRIVER LEFT THE SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 6:02AM. THE SITE SECURITY PERSONNEL HAD OBSERVED THAT THE TRAILER HAD LEAKED MATERIAL. THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE APPARENT LEAK. THE DRIVER STOPPED ALONG THE HIGHWAY INSPECTED THE TRAILER. HE NOTICED LIQUID SEEPING FROM A VALVE SO HE APPLIED VACUUM TO THE TRAILER, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. THE DRIVER TURNED AROUND AND WENT BACK TO THE PLANT.     AT APPROXIMATELY 6:52AM THE HE WAS BACK AT THE PLANT AND THE MATERIAL WAS OFF LOADED FROM THE TANKER AND INTO A BULK STORAGE TANK AT THE PLANT.     THE BULK TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO A THIRD PARTY DOT TRAILER INSPECTION VENDOR (SEE COMMENT BELOW).    THE PLANT PERSONNEL CALLED FROM AN EXTERNAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WHO INSPECTED THE TRUCK'S PATHWAY. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS FOUND TO HAVE EVAPORATED OFF THE ROAD SURFACE. AT THE SITE THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR CLEANED UP AREAS WHERE THE BULK TRAILER WAS STAGED OR HAD STOPPED.
column169: THE BULK TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO A THIRD PARTY TRAILER SHOP FOR AN INSPECTION OF THE VALVES. VALVES WERE INSPECTED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW VALVES THAT HAD TEFLON GASKETS. THE BULK TANKER WAS TESTED BY THE VENDOR AFTER THE SERVICE WORK WAS COMPLETED. OTHER TRAILERS THAT COULD BE USED TO TRANSPORT THIS MATERIAL HAVE HAD THE VALVES INSPECTED AND REPLACED WITH TEFLON GASKET EQUIPPED UNITS.    A TRADEBE TRUCK SHOP MANAGER INSPECTED THE TRAILERS AND ASSOCIATED PAPERWORK BEFORE ANY UNIT WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE.    A DRIVERS MEETING WAS HELD BY TRADEBE. THIS SERVICE AREA HELD A DRIVERS MEETING. THIS INCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED WITH THE DRIVERS ALONG WITH OTHER DOT TOPICS.

column168: On July 2, 2016 at 18:15 hours personnel in the CSXT Radnor Yard, discovered PROX 75128, a loaded tank car of ethylene glycol, was leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Shell Chemicals, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2016-07-02-00178). SWS, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product leaking from a sample line valve that was not in closed position and secondary securement plug less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Rick Ferguson).  The sample line valve was closed and the secondary securement plug installed wrench tight.  The car was released for transportation.  No Special switching move was required.    NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60  Cause Code: 145
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On July 6, 2016 at 11:07 hours, in the CSX Knoxville Yard, DOWX 74284, a loaded tank car of Ethyl Acrylate, was discovered to be leaking vapor from the manway cover of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Union Carbide Corp, was notified via CHEMTREC (report 2016-07-06-00159).   Joseph McCann, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, found the cause to be due to three of eight manway cover bolts less than hand tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Corey Becnel 225-206-2419)).  The manway cover securement bolts were all secured tool tight and the car was released for transportation.     NARRI Severity Index:   5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80  NAR Tank Car Cause Code: 200
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 07/15/16 at 0732 hours (Eastern Time) it was reported at Pascagoula Yard (CSXT), located in Pascagoula, MS, that tank car TILX304701, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, may be leaking.  CSX crews detected an odor of ammonia coming from the area of this car.  Local fire department was contacted and responded, United States Environmental Services (CSX Hazmat Contractor), and Hazmat Manager Trent Page responded.  The local fire department confirmed that the car was leaking.  USES and H/M Trent Page arrived onsite.  H/M Trent Page notified the shipper, Trammo (Dori Hester) and requested a local shipper contact.  Trammo, Dori Hester, provided Alan Bees with Trammo.  Alan responded to assist.    The shippers employee and USES confirmed the following: liquid line valve (B end) partially open, liquid line plug (B end) less than tool tight and unsecured, sample line plug less than tool tight/ unsecured, and the thermometer well cap unsecured.  The liquid line was closed and all plugs were secured.    A secondary inspection revealed that there was a constant leak coming from the pressure plate that was unable to be secured.  Hazmat Manager Trent Page contacted FRA inspector Gene Booker and Hazmat Director Mike Austin contacted FRA Kevin Blackwell and requested emergency permission to move this car for offloading in the interest of public safety back to the shipper facility in Pascagoula located approximately less than 2 miles by rail away.  Permission verbally granted by both.  Local fire and EMA director along with Mississippi State DEQ hazmat agreed to move the car in the interest of public safety.    Car was returned to shipper in Pascagoula for offloading.  Note:  The waybill reflects Trammo as the shipper with a Sutton, FL address.  The actual pickup location is at MISSISSIPPI PHOSPHATES CORP, 601 INDUSTRIAL RD, PASCAGOULA, MS 39567.  The CSX mainline was shut down for approximately 6 hours during this incident.  The CSX Yard was evacuated during this incident.          NAR Code: 117 (5 pts) Liquid Line Valve less than tool tight    5(5+3+9) x (2+4) = 510 NARRI         Pascagoula, MS  07/15/16  TILX304701  Anhydrous Ammonia

The car mover began backing the 3 cars down the spur when it was discovered the rail car breaking system was not pressurized.  The rail car mover brakes were applied but this had no effect on the speed.  The cars and the car mover traveled approximately 3,400 feet when they were derailed by the fix track de-railer located before the Union Pacific mainline.  The three cars rolled and one car was leaking from the top fill valve which was now positioned on the side (3 O'clock).  Univar personnel were able to stop the leak by driving a wooden spike into the valve body.  Emergency response contractors were hired to transfer the remaining product to an empty rail car last containing the same material.  The released material was contained by diking the area and covering the ground with plastic.  The soil was removed with heavy equipment and placed in roll off containers for disposal. The 2 rail cars that did not leak were evacuated in the same fashion.
column169: The training requirements and operator qualifications for performing rail car movements are under review.  Minimum changes will include professional, third party training and competency testing of all operators approved for rail car moving activities.

column168: During a routine yard check, liquid was noticed running out of a third party's trailer in the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility.  Upon opening the door, it was found that the load consisted of cardboard cartons of bleach That were shrink wrapped and double stacked in their original packaging.  The weight of the top pallets had crushed the bottom ones causing approximately 20 gallons of material to leak.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the mess-over-packing the crushed plastic bottles and soaked cardboard into 30 salvage drums along with the absorbent pads used to clean the trailer floor.  The shipment was then expedited into the intended waste disposal facility for handling.
column169: The shipper/third party carrier never should have double stacked the pallets.  The weight of the pallets was too much for the bottom pallets to support.  The generator and the third party hauler were notified of the incident.

column168: A box truck picked up a shipment of hazardous waste and returned to the intermediate truck transfer facility.  Upon opening the back door, it was noticed that one drum had some of the waste paint running down the side onto the truck floor.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spill with absorbent pads.  The lid was noticed to have bulged on one side.  It was found that part of the gasket was missing.  The lid, ring and gasket were replaced on the drum and the absorbent pad was placed into the drum.  The drum lid was closed per the applicable drum closure specs and the shipment was loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The shipper was notified of the incident and agreed to more closely check old drums and gaskets prior to loading.

column168: This incident pertains to a release of a UN2735 Amines liquid, corrosive. A total of (2) - 5 gallon plastic pails were damaged and released approximately 10 gallons of material due to improper blocking and bracing on the trailer. These pails were not secured or strapped to a pallet and fell to the trailer floor during transit. The release impacted a portion of the trailer floor and concrete parking lot. The release duration was over time during transit. No soils, drains, or waterways were impacted. An environmental service contractor was dispatched and this release was cleaned up in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.

column168: An RTS driver called at 1100 indicating that he was in Detroit Ml, where he had just completed his second stop of an LTL load - July 1, 2016. While at his second stop, the RTS driver noticed liquid on the floor of his truck. There was a container with a slow leak.The Driver had stopped at Gage, his first LTL stop, and picked up 9 five gallon pails and 16 55-SL drums. At the time of the Gage pickup he was suspicious of one container's integrity. When the driver got to his next stop he noticed liquid on the truck floor. The Gage product codes' are 32015 - 2 steel drums; 32101 7 steel drums/32103 7 steel drums; 32011 - 8 five gallon pails; 32014 -1 five gallon pail.Logistics arranged for an outside company to meet the driver in an isolated parking area. The driver and outside contractor over packed the leaking container, placed absorbent down in the truck and cleaned up. No material left the truck. A bottom seam on the drum appeared to have failed. The cause appeared to have been too much pressure being applied by the customers drum loader (mechanically squeezes the drums to lift and load).
column169: The shipper was notified about the integrity of the drums. RTS communicated that containers must be intact and pose no threat of leakage or spillage./

column168: On 07/22/16 at 17:52 hours (Eastern Time) it was reported at Gentilly Yard (CSXT), located in New Orleans, LA, that tank car GLNX24131, a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, N.O.S. (Fatty Alcohols Cl2), was leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  CSX personnel applied a containment bucket under the car and isolated it. Local fire department was contacted and responded and United States Environmental Services (CSX Hazmat Contractor) responded. USES confirmed that the bottom outlet valve was in the closed and locked position and was actively leaking from the BOV.  The BOV cap was also less than tool tight.  USES was able to secure the release by tightening the BOV cap and adding multiple fresh gaskets to the BOV cap. The shipper Stolt Nielsen USA Inc (Gabriel Gomez and Richey Austin) were notified. The shipper was requested by CSXT to provide tank trucks for a product transfer.    A product transfer was conducted by USES on 07/24/16 and this car is now a residue.  The car will be cleaned and purged, OTMA-3 applied for by shipper, and moved to home shop.        NAR Code: 551 (5 pts) Bottom Outlet Valve - Other    5(2+3+1) x (2+0) = 60 NARRI         New Orleans, LA  07/22/16  GLNX24131  Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, N.O.S. (Fatty Alcohols Cl2)

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL
column168: Shielded cask used for radioactive material shipment arrived at destination with non-fixed contamination in excess of the limits in 49CFR173.443 for the mode of shipment (non-exclusive use). The cask was empty. There was no evidence of package damage, breach or failure. This cask is loaded underwater in nuclear spent fuel pools. The water in the pools is radioactive. The cask is decontaminated prior to shipment. The leaching phenomenon is well documented for these underwater loaded casks. Had the cask been shipped as "Exclusive Use", the limits in 49CFR173.443 would not have been exceeded. There was no release of radioactive material to the environment.
column169: The originating shipper was contacted and advised of the leaching phenomenon and advised to ship cask as "Exclusive Use" in the future. The site currently using the cask is performing extensive decontamination and verification surveys prior to shipment as well as shipping "Exclusive Use"

column168: Highway Transport Chemical unit was parked at a truck stop on break. CMV was parked on a grade. Truck stop employees woke driver and reported his trailer was leaking. material was seeping from rear wash out port. Bucket was placed under drips and speedy dry was used to absorb released material. HTC safety department was contacted and an environmental company was dispatched to the scene. Environmental clean up crew reported that leak had stopped prior to their arrival; they cleaned up trailer and a 30 feet by a few inches wide of contaminated concrete.   Driver then ascended the trailer and tightened the wash out port cap.     Shipment was delivered without further incident.     Prior to loading trailer had passed a trailer prep, held 10 psi for 10 minutes.       Post incident inspection revealed that the top edge of the threads on the wash out port nipple needed to be resurfaced.  There were dings on the top edge. Carrier has changed procedure to include thicker wash out cap gasket at all terminals.
column169: Carrier has implemented a thicker gasket for wash out caps and a special tool has been ordered to insure proper resurfacing of wask out port nipples.

column58: Fusible Pressure Relief Device or Element
column168: On 07/14/2016 a Trimac DOT407 trailer carrying UN2078 Toluene diisocyanate experienced a release of approximately 6 ounces of material to the body of the trailer.  No soils, drains or waterways had been impacted by the release. The release occurred from an improperly secured fusible cap.  The cap had been replaced earlier in the day and the new one had not been properly secured and tightened.  When the trailer was put under approximately 10 psi of pressure the fusible cap would leak.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the area and re-secure any loose fittings. The environmental contractor cleaned the side of the tank and re-secured the cap.  The tank was brought back to 10 psi and there was no further release from the fusible cap or any other closures. All waste was taken offsite and properly disposed of.

A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that the containers noted above had a small amount of moisture that had collected on the pallets they were sitting on. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to repackage the compromised containers into a lined alternative containers. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: The waste material was spent carbon from a water filtration process and it was determined that the carbon had been too wet to ship in the containers that were used.  The moisture seeped through the uncoated fabric of the containers.  Discussions were held with the contracting company that packaged the containers.  Moving forward the contracting company will implement procedures to remove excess moisture prior to placing the spent carbon in future 13H3 containers.

column168: At 1150 hours on 20 July 2016, a Federal Railroad Administration Inspector notified CSX Transportation personnel of the discovery of product on the outside of tank car INVX 29608 located in the CSX Parkersburg Yard. The car was isolated, access restricted, and all required regulatory notifications made.    CSX contracted Specialized Professional Services, Inc to respond for assistance. Initial investigation found significant solid product buildup under the top mounted protective housing and down both sides of the car. The solids were removed, and car was relocated in the yard for safer access. It was determined the point of release to be a defective vacuum relief device located inside the protective housing. The device was temporarily replaced with a blind flange in order to secure the release.    On 22 July 2016 CSX contracted SUNPRO, Inc to install a new vacuum relief device and perform qualification testing for movement of the car to destination and unloading.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 25 July 2016 at 1300 hours, CSX Transportation was notified via email from an Ohio Public Utilities Commissions Inspector of tank car NATX 50676 to be experiencing a constant vapor release from an activated Pressure Relief Device. All regulatory notifications were immediately conducted, shipper notified via CHEMTREC, and SUNPRO, Inc was contracted to respond on behalf of CSX Transportation and investigate.    SUNPRO personnel arrived at 1400 hours and discovered the Pressure Relief Device was installed and not activating. The Vacuum Relief Device was found experiencing a consistent vapor release. The cause of the release was due to poor installation of the device, whereas it was hand tight into the flange / pressure plate interface and without any thread sealant.     The Vacuum Relief Device was removed appropriate thread sealant applied and reinstalled. Home Shop Decals were installed, and the car held in Clinton, OH for application and administration of a One Time Movement Approval.
column169: No additional comments.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: FDXU532747 (w/b containing Hazmat), was reported at the destination Stockton hub by the FedEx pickup driver on 7/6/16 at ~ 2045PT that it was  leaking at the rear doors (est. 8 drops/minutes rate). It was promptly parked in the containment area with absorbent under the affected areas. LARS was  notified and contacted FedEx Suann and ERTS who arranged cleanup through NRC Environmental.  NRC (Kyle Myers) inspected and found an IBC tote at the rear doors, leaking from a punctured tank due to a broken metal frame. Estimated release  was (a declared Haz Phosphonic Acid,UN3265) less than 5 gals. Solution was transferred to a good IBC tote + replaced into the trailer. The shipment  was not secured properly and package failure was the root cause.  NRC cleaned the affected container (in/out) , ground and the railcar deck it traveled on. Two waste drums have been placed in the container temporarily,  with NRC returning with a HazWaste transporter on 7/8/16 (am).
column169: Information shared with shipper including root cause (improper securement).  Shipper should review loading and securement practices to ensure that procedures are followed by loading personnel.

column168: A small amount of product was observed on the top and side of GATX 207325 near the combination housing.  Investigation indicated product releasing through liquid line valve and plug. Plug was tool tight and valve closed.  Ambient temperatures were elevated.  Pressure was released from car via the vapor valve which stopped the leak.      Release of an estimated one gallon of product occurred over a period estimated to be 2 hours or less.  No product reached the ground.    Car offloaded and mobile repair crew scheduled to replace valve, test and return car to service.
column169: Continue current practices.  Investigate and determine failure mechanism of the valve for this car if possible to determine if other action should be taken.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 7/7/16 at approximately 17:08, BNSF identified an odor emanating from the TILX 252173 in Barstow, CA train yard. The car was isolated and personnel kept from the immediate area while BNSF Hazmat responders inspected the car. Upon inspection it was found that 1 of 6 manway bolts were loose and the manway gasket was not properly aligned. This caused the manway gasket to be crushed and no longer able to seal as designed. Only vapor had been released, no liquid release from the residue tank car. The gasket was changed out and a new gasket installed. Responders inspected remaining tank car appliances and found no defects. The car was released for continued transportation to destination. There were no environmental impacts and estimated release volumes are only estimates based upon information received from the field.
column169: Systech Environmental should review post-unloading inspection procedures for tank cars that they handle.  Specifically, all closures should be tool tight and the manway gasket should be in operable condition to contain the commodity and vapor in the car.

column168: An interior inspection found 8 drums of hazmat at midpoint - 4 containing UN1814 // POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLUTION - with no cargo securement found throughout the load. The plug was tightened and the cargo reloaded and released back to the hub for continued movement.
column169: Shipper needs to review BNSF Railway's Intermodal Procedures relating to load securement to prevent future incidents.

column168: During a tank car blitz in the Roseville yard CPDX 108147 was found to have a vapor release from the pressure relief device valve. Water was placed in the stem guide so the valve was submerged for a bubble test. The valve failed the bubble test. A vapor bubble released from the valve every 5-10 seconds. The upper poppet (valve seat or cap) was removed, the outer o-ring was to small and did not seat in the poppet correctly. The o-ring was replaced, the PRD reassembled and the release was stopped. column168: On July 25, 2016 at 09:50 hours personnel in the CSXT Casky Yard discovered SHPX 208133, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S. leaking.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Renewable Products Marketing Group, was notified (CHEMTREC Report #2016-07-25-00070).  Joseph McCann, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, and Marion Environmental Inc (MEI), a CSX response contractor, were dispatched to the scene and found that residual product between the bottom outlet valve and bottom outlet valves secondary closure cap released. The bottom outlet valves secondary closure cap was secured and the faulty vacuum relief device was replaced with a pipe plug.  The car was moved to home shop for repair after obtaining a One Time Movement Approval from the FRA      NARRI: 5(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70  Cause Code: 1033, 149

ON 07-21-2016 AT 1400 HRS CSDT, I WAS ADVISED OF A TANK CAR LEAKING AT THE INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) RAILROAD YARD IN CALUMET CITY, IL. IHB OPERATIONS CENTER ADVISED CAR NUMBER GATX 20742, CONTAINING A FULL LOAD OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID UN 1789 PG II WAS DISCOVERED BY AN 1HB CONDUCTOR AND ENGINEER WHILE PASSING THE CAR ON ANOTHER TRACK. OPERATIONS CENTER AND TRAIN-MASTER BRUNO FROGLIA PLACED 2 TRACKS (CO1, CO2) IN THE YARD OUT OF SERVICE IN ORDER TO MITIGATE THE PROBLEM.     UPON ARRIVAL MYSELF AND SUNPRO SERVICES INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE DUE DO A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK. THE RUPTURE DISK WAS REPLACED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY O.5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT RELEASED. REMEDIATION OF THE PRODUCT WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY FLUSHING THE CAR AND BALLAST WITH LARGE AMOUNTS OF WATER. THE SHIPPER WAS BLEACHTECH AND THE TANK CAR CAME OUT OF PETERSBURG, VA. THE RAILCAR WAS IN ROUTE TO PVS CHEMICAL IN CHICAGO, IL. THERE WAS ALSO A PLACARD MISSING AND THE PRODUCT IDENTIFIER ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR WAS COVERED UP. column168: AT 1245 HOURS ON 7/28/2016 A CARMAN WORKING IN THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN KNOCHE YARD REPORTED A PROPANE LIKE SMELL. KCS ENV AND HAZMAT DEPT PERSONNEL RESPONDED. UPON INVESTIGATION TILX 309900 WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE PRESSURE PLATE -5 PRESSURE PLATE NUTS OVER THE LEAK AREA WERE LESS THAN 300 FOOT POUNDS. ADDITIONALLY THE A-END LIQUID VALVE PLUG AND THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG WERE ALSO DISCOVERED LOOSE AND LEAKING (ADDITIONAL FAILURE CODES 158/308/526) THE PRESSURE PLATE STUDS WERE TIGHTEN TO 600 FOOT POUNDS WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. THE A-END LIQUID VALVE PLUG AND THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG WERE ALSO TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT STOPPING THE LEAKS.     FILER NOTE ITEM: 19 THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED. THE ACTUAL AMOUNT RELEASED FROM THIS CONTAINER IS UNKNOWN TO THE CARRIER. TO DETERMINE ACTUAL AMOUNT RELEASED CONTRACT THE OFFEROR TO DETERMINE ACTUAL QUANTITY IN TAKE CAR AT ORIGIN (IF AVAILABLE) THEN CONTACT CONSIGNEE TO DETERMINE ACTUAL AMOUNT IN TANK CAR ONCE UNLOADED AND THE DIFFERENCES WILL BE THE TOTAL AMOUNT RELEASED. FILER NOTE: ITEM 27 AMOUNT IN PACKAGE WAS ESTIMATED BY THIS REPORT PREPARE BECAUSE THE EXACT INFORMATION IS NOT AVAILABLE TO CARRIER SHIPPER PROVIDED BULK QUANTITY ON SHIPPING PAPER AS 1 TANK CAR PER DOT REQUIREMENTS.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGO ,PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE OF INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS.(PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: A vehicle operated by Safety-Kleen Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the storage period, it was discovered that a small amount of material had escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the staging area were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column168: UTLX 12140 was interchanged with Texas Pacific on July 15, 2016. At that time Texas Pacific personnel noticed liquid leaking from the top of the rail car and refused the car back to BNSF. BNSF called out a hazmat contractor to inspect the car and found that the fill hole closure hinge was rusted through and no longer effective at securing the car. A small amount of hydrochloric acid had leaked out of the fill hole on to the top and side of the car. the BNSF contractor cleaned and neutralized the product. Cooper Natural Resources coordinated the transfer of the product and the empty car UTLX 12140 was transported to the car shop for repair.
column169: BNSF recommends re-training the shippers loading personnel to evaluate the fixtures on the rail car prior to loading. This spill could have been avoided if the shipper had noticed the hinge corrosion and had it repaired prior to loading.

column42: ETHANOL AND GASOLINE MIXTURE OR ETHANOL AND MOTOR SPIRIT MIXTURE OR ETHANOL AND PETROL MIXTURE, WITH MORE THAN 10% ETHANOL
column168: UTLX 208265 was in the repair facility in Pasco, WA when it was noted that liquid was leaking down the side of the car from the combination housing.  The car was moved outside of the building and assessed. It was noted that liquid was leaking from underneath the vapor valve assembly. The BNSF responder used a pipe wrench and was able to tighten the vapor valve slightly, until it hit the liquid valve. It was determined that the vapor valve was not tight enough due to this contact. The contractor arrived and removed the vapor valve assembly. The previous sealant was removed and the threads were cleaned. The liquid valve was slightly loosend to create clearance for the proper tightening of the vapor valve. The contractor applied Teflon tape to the threads and reinstalled the vapor valve. The liquid valve was then retightened tool-tight. The vapor valve was able to be tool-tightened properly and the car was noted as no longer leaking post-repair.    The shipper requested an OTMA for UTLX 208265 to be sent to final destination for offloading.
column169: Shipper must ensure that packaging and valves are properly secured prior to transport to alleviate any future hazardous materials releases. The valves need to be checked and ensured that they are tool-tight and the proper sealant is in place prior to the loading of tank cars at the facility. More attention by the loading personnel needs to occur to prevent these situations.

column25: Energy Logistics for Coleman Oil Company
column168: DBUX 300318 was identified as releasing during an inbound inspection.  BNSF Mechanical Responders identified the cause of the release was due to a loose liquid line valve as it threads into the threaded pipe connected to the liquid line flange.  The valve was removed and all threads were cleaned, thread tape was applied and the valve was secured.      A request to Randy Boyington, FRA to move DBUX 300318 from Spokane, WA to Hauser, ID under an OTMA-3 was granted verbally on 8/5/16.
column169: The shipper was contacted and notified of the release and cause of the release.  A request was also sent to the shipper to review their procedures for securement of loaded tank cars prior to offering for shipment.

column168: It was reported that improper packaging provided inadequate protection to the cargo and 2 - 50 pound paper bags of UN3260 Oxone PS16 Monopersulphate were ripped, releasing approximately 5 pounds of product to the trailer floor. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted and no other freight was damaged. A contractor cleaned up the material and placed the unreleased material into yellow bags to be shipped on to the consignee. 1 - 20 gallon container of waste was created and placed in the terminal OS&D with a corrosive label for future disposal.

There was no package failure. The driver was unloading the portable tank and noticed product leaking from a defective fitting on the discharge of the carrier's tractor-mounted pump. The driver turned off the pump which stopped the hazmat release. Estimated duration of the release is 15 minutes. Released hazmat was contained to the Consignee's concrete pad, mitigating the impact of the release.    An ERTS agent inadvertently filed a report that was unauthorized. As primary ERTS Agent for Quality Carriers, I contacted DOT by phone for assistance. The DOT representative assigned to this report advised me to file another DOT 5800 report to replace DOT 5800 Report No. E-2016080253 with Tracking No.674474. Please delete the older report and replace with this one.    Our Reference No. 61123

ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 99N AND 33 OUTSIDE OF DRUMRIGHT. THIS IS AN ALTERNATE TRUCK BY-PASS ROUTE. DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING A LEFT TURN ON TO STATE HWY. 99N. THE OPPOSING VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON HWY. 99 AND ATTEMPTED TO PASS A VEHICLE IN THE RIGHT LANE AND RODE UNDER THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER IN THE LEFT LANE.    1 TOTE RECEIVED A PIN-SIZED HOLE. A RESPONDER PLUGGED/PATCHED IT AND STOPPED THE LEAK. MATERIAL EVAPORATED.

column168: On July 25, 2016, a 5 gallon steel pail of UN1263 Thermo Adhesive arrived at the XPO Logistics terminal in Atlanta, GA damaged and leaking. The pail had been punctured by other freight due to a load shift caused by a lack of blocking and bracing.  The damaged pail released approximately 5 gallons to the trailer floor and parking lot.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release.  Granular absorbents were used to collect all free product.  The damaged pail was over packed and all waste was left on site for XPO personnel to manage.

Container APZU301274 was found leaking resin solution.  The shipper sent a contractor to clean up the spill and inspect the load.  Upon inspection the leak was found to be from an unsecured bungee hole plug on (1) 55 gallon drum of resin solution.  The drum was over-packed and the spill was cleaned up.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel found tank car GATX22283 leaking product from the top operating bottom outlet valve.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the leak was coming from the connection between the bottom outlet nipple and the bottom outlet valve.  The valve was found to be partially open.  The TOBO valve was closed to stop the leak.  The car owner sent Rescar to make repairs to the bottom outlet nipple.  The majority of the spill was caught in a spill pool.

Carrier at consignee off loading, smelled product,walked around trailer and found on the passenger side area at the air hose line was spraying product on the asphalt. Carrier shut down trailer. Carrier had environmental company on site to perform clean up. Carrier mechanical shop found that the air valve is bad/worn and allowed product into the air valve line which cause the product to stand/hold in the pipe on side connection which leaked at the threads on to the elbow pipe and ground. Carrier has replaced the bad air valve. No further issues.     event 61171

column168: A PICK UP OF 10 DRUMS WERE TRANSPORTED BACK TO SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY TO BE TRANSFERRED TO THE 10 STORAGE AREA. WHILE PREPPING THE TRUCK FOR OFFLOAD IT WAS DISCOVERED BY SMELL THAT THERE WAS A LEAK OF THE MATERIAL BEING TRANSPORTED. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS IDENTIFIED AS WE SAW A PIN HOLE NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM OF THE SEAM. WE TILTED THE DRUM TO A 45 DEGREE ANGLE TO STOP THE LEAK. WE PLUGGED/ PATCHED THE HOLE SECURING THE PATCH WITH DUCK TAPE AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM. ALL COMPANY ALERTS WERE MADE AT THE TIME. WE WIPED THE DIAMOND PLATE FLOOR WITH ABSORBENT MATS AND DISPOSED OF THE MAT IN THE OVERPACK. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORT TO COMPANY AUTHORITIES.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: DRIVER INDICATED THAT WHILE APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION, HE NOTICED A CONSTRUCTION AHEAD AND 3 CARS TO HIS LEFT THAT BEGAN TO MERGE INTO HIS LANE. AS HE APPROACHED, HE NOTICED THE THREE CARS COLLIDED IN A CHAIN REACTION. ONE OF THE CARS WAS FORCED INTO HIS LANE IN FRONT OF HIM. THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO STOP PRIOR TO COLLIDING INTO THE CAR. THE DRIVER FELT THE LOAD SHIFT FORWARD. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED 911. HE CHECKED TO MAKE SURE THERE WERE NO INJURIES. THE DRIVER THEN WENT TO CHECK THIS LOAD AND NOTICED THAT IT WAS LEAKING, AND CALLED TO REPORT THE SPILL. HE POURED DIRT OVER THE SPILL AREA TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. HE OPENED THE TRAILER AND NOTICED 3 BATTERIES HAD SLID OFF THE TOP LAYER FROM ONE OF THE PALLETS. THE STRETCH WRAP HAD TORN AND THE BATTERY ACID WAS LEAKING FROM ABOUT 5 MINUTES UNTIL IT WAS CONTAINED WITH DIRT. THE HAZ MAT CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO THE INCIDENT. HOWEVER, IT DID TAKE SOME TIME UNTIL THE CONTRACTOR GOT THERE DUE TO RUSH HOUR AND HE ALSO SAT IN TRAFFIC DUE TO ANOTHER TRAFFIC INCIDENT. THEY CLEANED THE SPILL ONCE THEY GOT THERE. THREE BATTERIES WERE OVER PACKED. ONCE THE LOAD WAS CLEANED UP, BLOCKED, AND BRACED, IT WAS RETURNED BACK TO THE EAST PENN WAREHOUSE TO OFF LOAD AND ASSESS THE DAMAGE OF THE LOAD.
column169: THE INCIDENT WILL BE USED AS A TRAINING TOOL    THE WAREHOUSE WILL BE USING ADDITIONAL STRETCH WRAP TO BETTER SECURE THE BATTERIES TO THE PALLETS.     MEASURES ARE BEING TAKEN TO PREVENT BATTERIES FROM SHIFTING IN THE VENT OF SUDDEN STOPS. LOAD LOCKS ARE BEING USED IN THE FRONT END AND THE BACK END OF LOADS.     DRIVER MEETING - STRESSED THE IMPORTANCE OF SAFE DRIVING, ESPECIALLY AROUND CONSTRUCTION ZONES. ALSO REMINDED DRIVERS THAT MOST AUTOMOTIVE DRIVERS ARE UNAWARE OF THE CHALLENGES THAT COMMERCIAL DRIVERS HAVE TO OVERCOME WHEN DRIVING LARGE VEHICLES.     SAFE DISTANCE AND SAFE SPEED IS MANDATORY!

column168: At 0855 on 07/06/2016 ERTS was contacted by Julie Young from Cherokee Insurance for Palmetto State Transportation. It was reported that a truck rear ended another semi which resulted in his cargo being thrown from the trailer. The truck is also leaking anti-freeze. After contacting Palmetto State, it was discovered that 4 cylinders are outside of the trailer and at least one is off-gassing. There is at least one cylinder inside the trailer that is also off gassing. The cylinders contained UN 1956. ERTS is dispatching Hull's Environmental to respond to the site and perform ER cleanup. An ETA of 2 hours was provided. Spalding county Battalion Chief Damien Vaughn called and stated that there are 4 cylinders on the ground, 1 is leaking, and an unknown number of cylinders are still off-gassing in the trailer. He is sending his Hazmat crew to make entry to the trailer and mitigate any further release. He also stated that there is approximately 500 gallons of foam surrounding the truck. At this time it is unknown what product is releasing.

column169: PLACE DUNNAGE BETWEEN THE SKID AND FREIGHT TO PREVENT NAIL PUNCTURES.

column168: SEQUENCE OF EVENTS:  THE DRIVER STOPPED AT THE LOCATION (3700 W JUNEAU AVE) TO UNLOAD OTHER FREIGHT AND DISCOVERED THE DRUM LEAKING. THE DRIVER REPORTED THE LEAK TO THE PROPERTY PERSONNEL. THE PROPERTY PERSONNEL NOTIFIED THE MILWAUKEE FIRE DEPARTMENT (MFD)  WHO RESPONDED. THE DRIVER REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO EXPEDITED FREIGHT SYSTEMS (EFS). EFS CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT INC (EMI), AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANY. EMI CONTACTED OSI ENVIRONMENTAL A LOCAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND DISPATCHED A CREW TO THE SITE FOR CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL, THE MFD HAD ALREADY CONTAINED THE RELEASED MATERIAL. OSI THEN COMPLETED THE CLEANUP ACTIVITIES AND PREPARED THE WASTE FOR TRANSPORTATION. THE WASTE WAS SECURED AT THE LOCATION UNTIL DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS ARE COMPLETE.     PACKAGE FAILURE:  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS IMPACTED BY OTHER FREIGHT (STEEL CART ON WHEELS). THE CART HAD A STEEL PROTRUSION THAT IMPACTED THE DRUM WHILE IN TRANSPORT. THE IMPACT PUNCTURED THE DRUM CAUSING A HOLE APPROXIMATELY 3 INCHES BY 3 INCHES. THE LIQUID RELEASE FRO THE HOLE ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.
column169: RECOMMENDATION - 1 ESTABLISH A LOADING MANIFEST THAT REQUIRES MANIFEST NOTATION OF ITEMS REQUIRING SPECIAL BLOCKING AND BRACING TO ASSURE A LOAD REMAINS SECURED DURING TRANSIT.  RECOMMENDATION - 2 DURING THE SECUREMENT PROCESS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WITHIN A TRAILER, THE SECUREMENT ALSO INCLUDES THE ADDITION OF A SHIELD AROUND THE MATERIAL SUCH AS EMPTY PALLETS OR PLYWOOD.    ACTION TAKEN: THE DRIVER WAS RE-TRAINED ON HIS ROLE IN IDENTIFYING POTENTIAL HAZARDS AND ACTIONS THAT CAN OR COULD MITIGATE ANY LOSS.    THE DOCK EMPLOYEE WHO LOADED THE TRAILER AND FAILED TO MAKE SURE ALL MEASURES WERE TAKEN TO BLOCK AND BRACE THE LOAD PROPERLY HAS BEEN RETRAINED AND DISCIPLINED.

column17: ENVIRITE OF PENNSYLVANIA, INC. DBA US ECOLOGY, INC
column168: ENVIRTIE OF PENNSYLVANIA DRIVER WAS RETURNING TO THE FACILITY LOCATED IN YORK PA WITH A LTL VAN TRAILER CONTAINING TWELVE 275 GALLON IBC TOTES OF SULFURIC ACID. THE DRIVER PROCEEDED BACK TO THE FACILITY VIA INTERSTATE 81 SOUTH IN LEBANON COUNTY PA. HE ENTERED INTO A CURVE AND ENCOUNTERED A BACKLOG OF TRAFFIC CAUSING HIM TO HARD BRAKE. AS HE STARTED UP AN INCLINE. HE WAS ALERTED BY A PASSING MOTORIST THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING. HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF THE ROAD OBSERVED THE LEAK AND BEGAN CONTAINMENT OF THE LEAK BY UTILIZING THE 85 GALLON SPILL KIT OVERPAK AND IT CONTENTS. UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LOAD SECUREMENT WAS INSUFFICIENT AND FAILED TO RESTRAIN THE TOTES. THE SIX TOTES MOVED FORWARD INTO THE OTHER SIX TOTES STAGED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THE TWO FRONT TOTES SLID INTO THE FRONT AND WERE GOUGED UPON IMPACT BY THE CARGO SECUREMENT HARDWARE.
column169: THE TOTES WERE NOT PROPERLY LOADED AND SECURED AT THE 10-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY: 6 TOTES IN THE NOSE, 2 STRAPS; APPROXIMATELY 18 FOOT GAP; 6 MORE TOTES WITH ONE BAR AND FOUR STRAPS ON THE FRONT AND TWO STRAPS ON THE BACK. DRIVERS WERE RETRAINED ON CARGO SECUREMENT REGULATIONS 49 CFR 392.9. COMPANY OPERATING PROCEDURES WILL INVOLVE ALL CONTAINERS TOUCH WITH NO SPACE FOR MOVEMENT OF LOAD. A REVIEW REGARDING THE CALCULATION OF 50% SECUREMENT BASED ON LOAD WEIGHT WAS DISCUSSED. ENVIRITE OF PENNSYLVANIA. INC. WILL WORK WITH THE TRANSFER FACILITY REGARDING LOADING CONFIGURATION.

column168: Driver was at facility to offload material for disposal.  After offload was complete and the driver was instructed to rescale the tanker before leaving. The truck exited the facility and drove onto the road and into the driveway at the other end of the facility. Driver did not check to ensure the tanker was properly closed before moving the truck and tanker combination resulting in the residual material on the walls of the tank leaking out of the bottom valve that had been left open.  The spill went down the driveway of the facility onto the street in front of the facility and up the second driveway of the facility. Approximately 50 gal of material was spilled. A clean up crew was dispatched to the facility and they cleaned the roadway and driveways with clay absorbent and swept up the residue.  Two drums of waste waste was swept up. The clean up material was brought to the offerer's (Cycle Chem Inc. in Lewisberry, PA) location for disposal.
column169: Driver has been re-trained to always check his equipment prior to leaving a facility or before starting at the beginning of the day even if someone at the facility tells them that everything was closed or secured properly, and has been given a written warning.

column168: A 48 QUART COOLER WAS RECEIVED AT GEL LABORATORIES EXTERNALLY UNDAMAGED, BUT SURFACE CONTAMINATION SMEARS INDICATED 77.9 DPM/SQUARE CENTIMETERS. INNER CONTENTS WERE FIVE 500 ML GLASS BOTTLES CONTAINING A U-235 SOLUTION. TWO OF THE 500 ML GLASS BOTTLES WERE BROKEN, AND AN ESTIMATED 200-300 ML HAD LEAKED FROM THE COOLER. THE DELIVERING DRIVER AND VAN WERE RECALLED TO GEL LABORATORIES TO BE SURVEYED FOR CONTAMINATION. SURVEY RESULTS OF THE DRIVER AND VAN WERE NEGATIVE. THREE ULD'S (UNIT LOAD SERVICES) HAD TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE AND WERE LOCATED IN THE FEDEX EXPRESS SYSTEM. CONTAMINATION SURVEYS WERE ARRANGED TO BE PERFORMED, AND TWO ULD'S WERE NEGATIVE. THE ULD WHICH TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE FROM MEMPHIS TO CHARLESTON WAS STILL IN CHARLESTON AND AN APPROXIMATE SQUARE FOOT AREA IN THE BOTTOM OF THAT ULD WAS CONTAMINATED. GEL LABORATORIES DECONTAMINATED THE ULD AT THE CHARLESTON FEDEX EXPRESS FACILITY TO NO MEASURABLE DETECTABLE ACTIVITY.

column168: UNIT WAS BEING LOADED TO THE FRONT OF A CONTAINER BY CRANE. ONCE SEPARATED FROM THE CRANE, A FORKLIFT WAS BEING USED TO PUSH THE UNIT TO THE BACK OF THE CONTAINER. WHILE BEING PUSHED, THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR HEARD A LOUD POP AND NOTICED GAS EMITTING FROM THE UNIT. HE IMMEDIATELY FLED THE AREA. THE GAS WAS IDENTIFIED AS UN2857 CLASS 2.2 NON FLAMMABLE LIQUID. PER THE ERG AND MSDS, THE GAS WAS LEFT TO RUN OUT. FANS WERE PLACED TO AIR OUT THE CONTAINER BEFORE ANYONE ENTERED.     PERSONNEL WAS RESTRICTED WITHIN A 500 METER RADIUS OF THE CONTAINER. THE AREA WAS ALSO LEFT OPEN FOR VENTILATION ONCE THE SMELL HAD DISSIPATED FROM THE CONTAINER THE UNITS WERE ASSESSED. IT APPEARED THAT THE WOODEN PALLET HAD BROKEN AND PUNCTURE THE PIPING AT THE BOTTOM OF THE UNIT. PHOTOS WERE THEN GATHERED OF THE DAMAGED.
column169: WE WILL DISCUSS THE PACKING MATERIALS USED WITH TRANE TO ENSURE THAT UNITS ARE BETTER PACKED/PALLETIZED IN THE FUTURE.

Driver discovered shipper had applied 34 PSI (according to the cargo tank pressure gauge) after loading. column169: In many chemical plants, drivers are not allowed to climb the cargo tank ladder to check the dome are before leaving the plant. Shippers need to be required to have a location where drivers can safely check the top of the cargo tank before leaving the plant. The practice now is to make the driver leave the plant without having the opportunity to check their trailer as is required by regulations thus putting the driver in a situation of having to check the trailer "somewhere" down the road.

column168: SMAF ENVIRONMENTAL (SMAF) RESPONDED TO A BATTERY-ACID RELEASE RESULTING FROM A TRUCK ACCIDENT. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED ON JULY 5TH, 2016, ON OREGON HIGHWAY 78, MILEPOST 26.9 NORTHWEST OF CRANE, OREGON. THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 78, WHEN THE DRIVER REPORTEDLY SWERVED TO AVOID AN ANIMAL. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL, AND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER TURNED ONTO THEIR SIDES ACROSS THE HIGHWAY. THE ACCIDENT RUPTURED SEVERAL CONTAINERS OF BATTERY ACID IN THE CARGO TRAILER, WHICH LEAKED ONTO THE ROAD SURFACE AND THE HIGHWAY SHOULDER. SMAF DISPATCHED A RESPONSE SUPERVISOR AND TECHNICIANS TO THE SCENE TO SECURE THE SITE, PUMP FUEL FROM THE TRUCK TANKS, ASSIST THE TOWING COMPANY WITH THE RECOVERY, CLEAN THE HIGHWAY SURFACE, AND TO ASSESS THE SCENE AND PLAN FOR THE REMEDIATION EFFORT.     SMAF RETURNED TO THE SITE ON JULY 12TH TO EXCAVATE AND NEUTRALIZE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND REPLACE IT WITH CLEAN FILL MATERIAL. APPROXIMATELY 30 TONS OF ACID-IMPACTED SOIL WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND TRANSPORTED TO A LANDFILL FOR DISPOSAL AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE EXCAVATION WAS BACK-FILLED AFTER ON SITE PH TESTING CONFIRMED THAT THE REMAINING SOIL HAD BEEN NEUTRALIZED, AND THE SITE WAS RESTORED TO THE ORIGINAL GRADE.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: THE DRIVER OF A TRANSPORT TANKER CARRYING ETHANOL OVERTURNED ON INTERSTATE 35 NEAR GUTHRIE OK. IT WAS RAINING AND THE DRIVER TOOK EYES OFF ROAD WAY AND THEN OVER CORRECTED WHEN HE WAS LEAVING ROAD WAY CAUSING IT TO OVERTURN. A SMALL VALVE APPROXIMATELY 1/2 INCH WAS TORN OFF FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK RELEASING THE ETHANOL. ALSO THE 5 FILL PORTS FORM THE TOP OF THE TANKER WERE LEAKING AS WELL. THE 1/2 VALVE WAS PLUGGED BY FIRE DEPARTMENT. IT WAS ESTIMATED 250 GALLONS WAS LOST. RESPONSE TEAM TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING PRODUCT.
column169: DRIVER PAY MORE ATTENTION TO DRIVING.

column168: DURING A DOT INSPECTION IT WAS NOTICED THE TWO DRUMS HAD A FEW SMALL DRIPS COMING FROM TWO STEEL 55 GALLON DRUMS THAT WERE OPEN TOP DRUM. THE DOT OFFICER WANTED THE LEAK STOP. THE TEAM ENTER THE TRAILER AND UTILIZED A IMPACT WRENCH TO TIGHTEN THE LIDS OF THE TWO DRUMS OF CONCERN. THE LIDS WERE NOT TIGHT ENOUGH AND TEAM TIGHTEN THEM. NO FURTHER ACTION WAS NEEDED DOT OFFICER RELEASED THE TRUCK.

column168: Upon movement of BNSF 880615 in the Klamath Falls yard, a liquid surge of product released from underneath the protective housing, releasing approximately 35 gallons of product. A BNSF responder investigated the source of the leak and climbed to the top of the car. The seal was intact on the protective housing. The seal was cut, the housing lid opened, and the valves inspected. The liquid valve was noted as fully opened along with the cam-lock style cap off and lying on the pressure plate. The vapor valve was also noted as fully open, but the cam-lock cap was intact and secure.   The BNSF responder closed the liquid valve to prevent any further release of product. The cap was reinstalled and secured. A remediation contractor arrived onsite and cleaned the car and remediated the soil underneath.
column169: Shipper needs to review procedures on proper tank car securement. Shipper needs to ensure that all valves and caps are secured properly in place to prevent further releases of hazardous materials.

column168: While in-transit, the Portable tank was dropped for heating at an in-transit storage depot. Later, the driver picked up the portable tank for delivery and within a few miles he noticed product had released. Driver stopped to investigate and noticed the dome open and resting on its toggles.The release stopped when vehicle was parked. In addition, he noticed the released product had frozen onto the sides of the tank. Duration of the release is estimated to be approximately 10 minutes. The driver mitigated the effects of the release by bolting down the dome, then drove to the consignee.   DOT recommended to submit another DOT 5800 to replace DOT 5800 Report No.2016080251 Tracking No. 674472; inadvertently filed on 8.12.2016. column168: DRIVER WAS NEGOTIATING A LEFT CURVE DOWN A SMALL HILL. DRIVER STATED THAT A VEHICLE CAME AROUND THE CORNER ON HIS SIDE OF THE ROAD AND THAT HE MOVED HIS VEHICLE TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD QUICKLY CAUSING THE LIQUID TO SHIFT AND CAUSED THE TANKER TO ROLL AS HE WENT THROUGH THE CORNER. TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED MULTIPLE TIMES COMING TO REST IN SOME TREES AND BUSHES. AS THE TANK ROLLED IT DAMAGED SOME OF THE PIPING ON THE TRAILER AND WHEN IT CAME TO REST A LIMB CAUGHT ONE OF THE CABLES ATTACHED TO A VALVE ON TANK. THE LIMB SLIGHTLY OPENED THE VALVE ALLOWING GAS TO SLOWLY ESCAPE. WHEN RESPONSE CREW ARRIVED AND DISCOVERED THE VALVE THE CABLE WAS CUT AND VALVE CLOSED. THIS VALVE WAS OPEN FOR APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS BEFORE IT COULD BE SHUT DOWN BECAUSE IT WAS VAPOR AND VERY SMALL LEAK IT COULD NOT BE DETERMINED THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOST.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: Driver started loading at the Grand Forks terminal at 0933 and finished at 0944.  He then proceeded onto Interstate 29 heading north to his destination.  Around 1000 driver loss control of his semi and went off the road near mile marker 152.  He rolled both the semi and the fully loaded trailer.  In the rollover one compartment on the trailer was damaged and began leaking the diesel fuel into the ditch.  Another motorist on the road saw the accident and called it into the police.  The owners, Manvel PD and Fire Dept, Grand Forks PD and Fire Departments and Highway Patrol responded to the incident.  The driver was extracted from the semi and transported by ambulance to Altru Hospital in Grand Forks ND.  The weather was clear and roads were dry at the time of the incident and did not factor into the accident.  It was later determined the driver has been driving under the influence of alcohol.     DUB Construction, PDQ Sanitary Services and two Northdale Oil empolyees were involved in the cleanup of the fuel that spilled.  Jim's Towing was called to haul both truck and trailer out of ditch and to an off-site location.

CLEAN HARBORS OF BRIDGEPORT, NEW JERSEY WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. CLEAN HARBORS RECOVERED THE FREE PRODUCT/LIQUID FROM THE AREA, WHICH WAS CONTAINERIZED INTO RECOVERY DRUMS AND A DOT-407 (STAINLESS STEEL)TANKER ON SITE, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. CLEAN HARBORS ASSESSED RAIL BED/SOILS FOR IMPACT AND COORDINATED RECOVERY EFFORTS. GROUNDWATER & ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (GES) WAS DEPLOYED TO ASSIST IN ASSESSMENT AND MONITORING. GES WILL PERFORM REQUIRED ANALYTICAL SAMPLING AND REGULATORY FOLLOW UP. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON SATURDAY 07/16/2016 AT APPROX 1030, A LOTT OIL COMPANY TRANSPORT FULLY LOADED WITH 8500 GALLONS OF E-10 UNLEADED GASOLINE WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON LA HWY 9 AFTER LOADING AT THE ARCADIA, LA TERMINAL. A PASSENGER VEHICLE TRAVELING AT AN ESTIMATED HIGH RATE OF SPEED CROSSED THE CENTER LINE OF THE HIGHWAY AND STRUCK THE FRONT DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE TRUCK-- CAUSING OUR DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL, PARTIALLY LEAVE THE ROADWAY, AND SUBSEQUENTLY ROLLED THE CAB AND TRAILER ON IT'S SIDE. THE OTHER DRIVER ALSO SPUN OUT AND REVERSED DIRECTION INTO THE DITCH. THE IMPACT CAUSED ABOUT A 4" TEAR BEAR THE TOP OF COMPARTMENT 5, AND A LARGER PUNCTURE IN COMPARTMENT 1 JUST BEHIND THE CAB WHERE THE MAJORITY OF THE RELEASE OCCURRED.     FIRE, EMS, AND STATE POLICE HAZ MAT WERE ON THE SCENE QUICKLY, AND FOAMED THE TRUCK AND SPILL ALLOWING THEM TO RETRIEVE OUR DRIVER, CASEY CASCIO, WHO WAS LATER ATTENDED TO WITH NO LIFE THREATENING INJURIES. THE OTHER DRIVER WAS ALSO TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND LATER RELEASED AS WELL.     OVER THE NEXT 6 HOURS OR SO. LOTT PERSONNEL AND TAS ENVIRONMENTAL STAFF WORKED TO CONTAIN THE REA OF RELEASE WITH CONTAINMENT BOOM AND ABSORBENT PADS, AND TO TAP THE COMPARTMENTS AND TRANSFER THE GASOLINE TO OTHER VEHICLES. APPROX 6800 OF LIQUID WAS RECOVERED ON SITE, ALLOWING THE VEHICLE TO BE UPRIGHTED AND TOWED BACK TO TOWN. AN ADDITIONAL SEVERAL HUNDRED GALLONS WAS RECOVERED FROM COMPARTMENTS AND BELLY VALVES UPON RETURN, BRINGING THE TOTAL ESTIMATED RELEASE TO 1588 GALLONS.     EMERGENCY 811 UTILITY LOCATION WAS DONE ON SUNDAY, THE 17TH, AND EXCAVATION AND CLEAN UP BEGAN MONDAY, THE 18TH UNDER THE DIRECTION OF TAS ENVIRONMENTAL AND LA DEQ. SITE IS PENDING SOIL SAMPLE ANALYSIS AT THIS TIME.
column169: TRAINING HAS BEEN A CONSISTENT PART OF LOTT OIL CULTURE FROM DATE OF HIRE FOR ALL EMPLOYEES, BUT ESPECIALLY HAZ MAT CERTIFIED DRIVERS. EFFORTS WILL CONTINUE TO MAKE OUR DRIVER AND EQUIPMENT THE SAFEST ON THE ROAD. WE FEEL THAT EVEN THOUGH THE VEHICLE WILL BE TOTAL LOSS, THE FACT THAT IT WAS ONE OF OUR NEWEST TRAILER (LESS THAN 3 MONTHS OLD) EQUIPPED WITH NEW DISC BRAKING SYSTEM AND ANTI ROLLOVER TECHNOLOGY HELPED TO KEEP THE ACCIDENT FROM BEING WORSE, AND QUITE POSSIBLY INCREASING THE LIKELIHOOD OF THE DRIVER SUSTAINING ONLY MINOR INJURIES.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1145AM ON 07/30/2016 DRIVER ARRIVES AT LOADING FACILITY, RIBOST TERMINAL AT APPROXIMATELY 12PM. DRIVER IS GIVEN PERMISSION FROM RIBOST TERMINAL OPERATOR TO START LOADING. TRANSPORTER TRAILER FILLS UP IN A APPROXIMATELY 10MIN FROM THERE FOR UNKNOWN REASON TERMINAL OPERATOR IMPLEMENTS THE KEY BY MANUALLY AND RESTARTS THE LOADING BEFORE THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO OPEN THE OTHER COMPARTMENT, CAUSING AN OVERFILL AND SPILLING APPROX 126 GALLONS. THERE FORWARD RIBOST TERMINAL MANAGEMENT AGREED TO BETTER TRAIN ALL TERMINAL OPERATORS TO BETTER COMMUNICATE WITH DRIVERS' VERIFYING THAT ALL EMPTY COMPARTMENTS ARE OPEN TO LOAD AND FULL COMPARTMENTS ARE CLOSED SO THAT NO PRODUCT BYPASSES TO OTHER COMPARTMENT.

column168: WHILE LOADING CRUDE OIL AT THE JETTA OPERATING LEASE. THE JUMPER HOSE THAT CONNECTS THE PUMP TO THE LOADING LINE ON THE TANKER VIBRATED LOOSE. THE CAMLOCK EARS UNLOCKED AND THE HOSE DISCONNECTED FROM THE FITTING. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND CLOSE THE VALVES. ROUGHLY 2.5 BBLS OF CRUDE OIL SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND OF WHICH 2 GALLONS RAN INTO DARB CREEK. THE KY DEP AND NRC WERE CONTACTED. ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE PLACED IN THE STREAM TO CAPTURE THE SHEEN. THE CONTAMINATED GRAVEL REMOVED FROM THE PROPERTY AND PROPERLY DISPOSED.
column169: SINCE THE SPILL OCCURRED ENLINK MIDSTREAM, THE PARENT COMPANY OF KENTUCKY OIL GATHERING HAS INSTITUTED THE USE OF CAMLOCK EAR STRAPS AND PINS RESTRICTING MOMENT OF THE EARS WHILE LOADING OR UNLOADING.

column168: Our tractor and dump trailer was hauling EAF Dust from Nucor Steel, Crawfordsville, IN to Horsehead Corp., Chicago, IL on 7/21/2016.  At approximately 0745 the truck left the roadway and overturned in the median, spilling 2 tons of EAF Dust in the median.  The driver reported that he thought a tire blew, causing him  to lose control of the vehicle.  The Indiana State Police Officer that reported to the scene of the crash was also an accident investigator.  According to his findings in the Crash Report, he was unable to locate any evidence that a tire had blown.  He also reported there were no environment or vehicle contributing circumstances to the cause of the accident.  We contacted SET Environmental, Chicago, IL to provide the Emergency Response Services for the clean-up and remediation of the accident site.  When the tractor and trailer left the highway, it hit the guardrail, causing the tractor and trailer to rollover and ultimately come to a stop in the median on its side.  Upon impact of the top corner of the trailer with the ground, the roof on the trailer was partially torn off, therefore releasing 2 tons of EAF Dust on the ground.  SET Environmental and Gardner Transport Services, Inc. worked together toward clean-up and remediation and the spill site was secured by 1730 on 7/22/16.
column169: Gardner Transport Services, Inc. holds quarterly (4) Safety Meetings each year.  Every Safety Meeting consists of teaching and reiterating the importance of safety, awareness of surroundings, being alert and well rested, and the absence of distractions while driving a commercial motor vehicle.  We used this incident as a teaching opportunity and provided additional training, specifically for hauling Hazardous Waste at the next quarterly Safety Meeting. Additionally, all drivers are required to complete Hazardous Materials Safety Training, as per the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration.  Since it was determined that the accident was not caused by an equipment failure or any environmental factors, we determined that the cause of the crash was human error. Upon completion of the accident investigation by the Indiana State Police and Gardner Transport Services, Inc., we terminated the driver.
